node.attribute:
Takes a reference to XML (in the form of a String) and the specified XPath Query is run against the XML and returns the results in a form of a delimited list. The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) organization provides the XPath specification (http://www.w3.org).

Inputs:
xml - The XML (in the form of a String)

xpathQuery - The XPath Query that is wanted to be run. See Examples in Notes section below.

delimiter- The delimiter used to separate values in the returnResult list. 

Default value: ,

Result Value:
returnResult - The result of the operation. If multiple XPaths are defined then this will add the delimiter between each value. There is no final delimiter.

Notes:
Examples:
The XPath Query can be specified as a single query in a format similiar to the following:
/employees/employee[@id="3"]/*[name()="name" or name()="jobDescription" or name()="salary" or name()="managerId"]/text()

This would return the following results:
Goofy,tester,$50,1

Or if more then one XPath query needs to be specified, populate xpathQuery using the XPath concat function.  As an example here is sample of a xpathQuery value using XPath concat function:
concat(/employees/employee[@id="2"]/name/text(),',',/employees/employee[@id="2"]/jobDescription/text(),',',/employees/employee[@id="2"]/managerId/text(),',',/employees/employee[@id="2"]/salary/text())

The output using the concat xpathQuery input would return the following results:
Donald Duck,Lead Coder,1,$50

The examples above use the following xml string value:


  
    Mickey Mouse
    Chief
    $100
    
  
  
    Donald Duck
    Lead Coder
    $50
    1
  
  
    Goofy
    tester
    $50
    1
  
  
    Pluto
    Coder - grade 1
    $25
    2

ignoreCase - If set to 'true', then the comparison ignores case considerations. responses:

false - If the two strings are not equal

Counts from one number to another number. 
Inputs:
from - The number to start counting at.
to - The number to count to.
incrementBy - The number to increment by while counting. If unspecified this is 1. If you wanted to count 2,4,6,8 this would be 2.
reset - If true, then the counter will restart counting from the beginning.

NOTE: These values must be between -9223372036854775808 and 9223372036854775807

Returns:
The number that was just counted.

Note: the primary result is resultString, Result can also be used. result (All lower case) should not be used as it is the response code.

Responses:
has more - Not yet done counting.
no more - Done counting. This will only be returned once, then counting restarts.
failure - Something went wrong.

Performs a mathematical operation on two numbers or strings

Inputs:
value1 - The first value.
value2 - The second value.
operation - The operation to perform (+ - * ^ / > < == != >= <=).

Responses:
success -  The operation completed successfully. If a boolean operation, it evaluated to true.
failure - Something went wrong or the boolean operation returned false.

Returns:
The raw result of the operation, for boolean values this is true or false.

Returns:
Field 1 - The first value. Here for compatibility
Field 2 - The second value. Here for compatibility
Field 3 - The operation. Here for compatibility
formatted_result - The formatted result of the operation, for boolean values this is true or false.

Counts from one number to another number. 
Inputs:
from - The number to start counting at.
to - The number to count to.
incrementBy - The number to increment by while counting. If unspecified this is 1. If you wanted to count 2,4,6,8 this would be 2.
reset - If true, then the counter will restart counting from the beginning.

NOTE: These values must be between -9223372036854775808 and 9223372036854775807

Returns:
The number that was just counted.

Note: the primary result is resultString, Result can also be used. result (All lower case) should not be used as it is the response code.

Responses:
has more - Not yet done counting.
no more - Done counting. This will only be returned once, then counting restarts.
failure - Something went wrong.

Service to perform an HTTP GET via the Java HTTP Client

Inputs:
url - the url to attempt to retrieve.
username - the username to authenticate to url with.
password - the password for username.
timeout - a timeout after which the connection should be terminated, or 0 for no timeout.
useCookies - Enables cookie tracking. Cookies will be stored between consecutive calls. valid options are: true/false
followRedirects - specifies whether or not the get command should automatically follow redirects.
trustAllRoots - enables weak security over SSL. A SSH certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it. valid options are: true/false
proxy - a proxy to use when accessing the web site.
proxyPort - a port on the proxy to connect to.
proxyUsername - a username to use when connecting to the proxy.
proxyPassword - a password to use when connecting to the proxy.
encodeURL - perform URL encoding.
userAgent - if the HTTP header USER_AGENT needs to be overridden, pass in the value here
characterSet - the characterSet for HTTP Get request and response. Default is UTF-8.

Responses:
success - URL retrieved successfully.
failure - The url could not be retrieved.
